---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
const draft = true; // STAGED: remove this line on publish date
const faqSchema = {
  "@context": "https://schema.org",
  "@type": "FAQPage",
  "mainEntity": [
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "What should I do as a seller if my property is passed in at auction in Brisbane?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Immediately after a pass-in, your agent should bring the highest bidder to you or a private space to begin negotiations. Stay calm, be clear about your minimum acceptable price, and be prepared to negotiate. The post-auction window is often when a sale happens, because the highest bidder has already demonstrated their interest. Avoid making rash decisions in the emotion of the moment: you have the right to take the day to think before signing anything."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "How common are pass-ins at Brisbane auctions?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Even in strong markets, a meaningful proportion of auctions in Brisbane's inner east do not clear on the day. In competitive conditions, clearance rates for well-presented family homes in suburbs like Bulimba, Morningside, and Camp Hill typically run between 60 and 75 per cent, meaning 25 to 40 per cent of auction campaigns end in a pass-in. A pass-in is not a failure: a substantial majority of passed-in properties in the inner east sell within a week or two through post-auction or private treaty negotiations."
      }
    },
    {
      "@type": "Question",
      "name": "Can I adjust my reserve price after a Brisbane auction pass-in?",
      "acceptedAnswer": {
        "@type": "Answer",
        "text": "Yes. Once the auction concludes without a sale, you are under no obligation to maintain your original reserve. You can negotiate at any price you choose in the post-auction private treaty process. Many vendors who set an aspirational reserve adjust their expectations after receiving honest buyer feedback during the campaign, and the post-auction negotiation is where that adjustment happens."
      }
    }
  ]
};
---
<Layout title="What Happens When a Brisbane Property is Passed In at Auction? | Daniel Gierach Property" description="A pass-in is not the end of the road. Here is what it means for you as a seller, how to negotiate after the auction, and when to shift to private treaty." draft={draft}>

<script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify(faqSchema)} />

<article style="background:var(--color-surface-0);min-height:100vh;">

  <!-- Hero -->
  <div style="background:#0a0806;padding:8rem 0 3rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8">
      <a href="/insights" style="display:inline-flex;align-items:center;gap:0.5rem;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.65rem;font-weight:700;letter-spacing:0.14em;text-transform:uppercase;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.35);text-decoration:none;margin-bottom:2rem;transition:color 0.2s;"
        onmouseover="this.style.color='#f5d07a'" onmouseout="this.style.color='rgba(240,236,228,0.35)'">
        &larr; All Articles
      </a>
      <span style="display:block;font-family:var(--font-sans);font-size:0.6rem;font-weight:800;letter-spacing:0.2em;text-transform:uppercase;color:#f5d07a;margin-bottom:1rem;">Sellers &middot; 5 min read</span>
      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        What Happens When a Brisbane Property is Passed In at Auction?
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        A pass-in is not a failure. It is a change of process. Here is how to handle the next 48 hours, and how to protect your sale outcome after the auction ends.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Choosing to sell by auction carries a specific risk that every vendor accepts when they sign the auction authority: the property may not sell on the day. If bidding does not reach your reserve price, the auctioneer declares the property passed in and the auction concludes without a signed contract. For vendors who have spent four to six weeks preparing, presenting, and waiting through a campaign, that moment can feel like a setback. It does not have to be. What happens in the hours and days after a pass-in often determines whether the campaign ends in a strong result or a long and uncertain private treaty tail.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The immediate post-auction window and why it matters</h2>
      <p>In Brisbane's inner east, the universal practice after a pass-in is for the agent to bring the highest registered bidder into a private negotiation with the vendor. This first right of negotiation for the highest bidder is disclosed to all registered bidders at the start of the auction, so it is not a surprise to anyone. The buyer who bid the highest has already demonstrated, publicly, that they are willing to pay close to or up to a certain level. They are warm. They have done their due diligence. They have turned up on a Saturday afternoon prepared to buy. That combination rarely applies as cleanly at any other point in the selling process.</p>

      <p>The post-auction negotiation typically happens quickly, within one to two hours of the auction. The agent manages the conversation, relaying positions between you and the buyer (or facilitating a direct discussion, depending on your preference and the dynamic). You can accept an offer at any price you choose. There is no obligation to stick to your reserve once the auction has concluded without a sale. If you set your reserve at a level the market would not support on the day, the post-auction conversation is when you get honest, real-time feedback on what a willing buyer will actually pay. Many vendors find this conversation more informative than anything else that happened during the campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">How to approach the negotiation as a seller</h2>
      <p>The most important thing you can do in a post-auction negotiation is stay calm and know your actual bottom line before the conversation starts. Ideally, this conversation happens before the auction day: you and your agent agree in advance on what you will accept if the property passes in, so you are not making that decision under emotional pressure with buyers waiting outside. Your agent should walk you through realistic post-auction scenarios as part of pre-auction preparation, not as an afterthought once the hammer has fallen short of your reserve.</p>

      <p>Do not make the common mistake of treating the pass-in as an insult and walking away from a buyer who bid close to your reserve. The highest bidder at an auction has told you their maximum via the public bidding process, but that number can move in private negotiation, particularly if you can offer something in return: a flexible settlement, a longer or shorter term than they expected, or simply a clean unconditional contract rather than one with finance and building conditions. Your agent should understand what the buyer's motivations are and what flexibility exists on both sides. Good post-auction negotiation is not just about price. It is about finding the combination of terms that creates agreement.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The risk a pass-in creates for public perception</h2>
      <p>A pass-in is publicly visible. Other buyers who were watching the auction but did not register to bid, prospective buyers who will see the listing in the following days, and the market broadly all know what happened. The risk is that the pass-in signals a gap between vendor expectations and buyer demand, which makes some buyers more cautious about engaging in private treaty negotiations. They may assume that the vendor is holding out for a price the market will not pay, or that there is something about the property that put buyers off on the day.</p>

      <p>Your agent's public communication after a pass-in matters. A confident, clear message that the property is available via private treaty and that negotiations are underway keeps momentum going. A vague or evasive response to buyer inquiries creates uncertainty that erodes interest. The first 48 hours after a pass-in are when buyer interest is still warm and the campaign has the best chance of converting. If you do not secure a sale from the highest bidder, your agent should be making contact with the next registered bidder and any other qualified buyers who attended open homes during the campaign before the news cycle moves on.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">When to switch to private treaty and how to reset expectations</h2>
      <p>If the post-auction negotiation with the highest bidder does not produce a result and contact with remaining registered bidders does not generate an offer, you move into a private treaty campaign. The question at this point is whether your price expectations are realistic relative to what the market has told you. If multiple registered bidders at the auction reached a similar ceiling and the highest bid fell 10 to 15 per cent below your reserve, that is not noise: it is signal. The market has spoken clearly about where buyer demand sits for your property at its current presentation and price.</p>

      <p>Resetting your reserve downward to meet the market is not a surrender. It is an acknowledgement that price and buyer demand are in dialogue, and that your opening position needs adjusting. Most inner-east vendors who reduce their asking price to within 5 per cent of where genuine buyer competition topped out at auction find a buyer quickly in the weeks that follow. The buyers are there. They showed up. The adjustment required is usually modest once the emotional distance between your reserve and the market's response is honestly assessed.</p>

      <p>The other option, maintaining your price and running a longer private treaty campaign, is viable when you have genuine flexibility on timing and are confident that buyer demand will increase, for example because you are selling ahead of a significant infrastructure announcement or school catchment change that will bring more buyers into your suburb. But patience has a cost: holding costs continue, your property ages on the market, and each additional week that passes without a sale creates a question in buyers' minds about why it has not sold. The right strategy depends on your circumstances, the quality of the feedback you received during the campaign, and an honest assessment of where the market is heading in your specific suburb and price bracket.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What causes most pass-ins in Brisbane's inner east</h2>
      <p>Most pass-ins have the same root cause: a reserve set above the level that genuine buyer competition will support on the day. That gap can exist because the property was appraised optimistically during the listing process, because the vendor's expectations were anchored to a comparable sale from a different market period, or because buyer feedback during open homes was not clearly communicated or acted on before auction day.</p>

      <p>The most common pattern in inner-east auctions is that buyer feedback during the first two weeks of the campaign signals where genuine competition is likely to top out. If open-home attendees are consistently telling your agent that the property is appealing but the price feels high, and no price adjustment is made before auction day, a pass-in is the likely result. The solution is not to lower the reserve to a level you are not comfortable with: it is to take the campaign feedback seriously and have an honest conversation with your agent about where buyer demand actually sits, before auction day rather than after.</p>

      <div style="padding:1.5rem;background:rgba(245,208,122,0.06);border-left:3px solid #f5d07a;">
